684248	686363	Wet-mesic Prairie shares a surprising number of understory species that reach peak abundance in both communities (Packard 1993, Pruka 1994). These understory species (e.g., <i>Dodecatheon meadia, Galium boreale, Hypoxis hirsuta, Lathyrus venosus, Silene stellata</i>) appear to require both high direct sunlight levels and low moisture stress conditions. Thus they are found both in open prairies that are wet enough to meet their transpiration needs and in openings that are open-canopied enough to meet their light needs but closed-canopied enough to reduce transpiration stress and allow them to compete on drier soils (Pruka 1994, Bray 1958). 684905	688824	stands are dominated or codominated by <i>Pascopyrum smithii</i>, but <i>Eleocharis acicularis</i> is absent and <i>Hordeum jubatum</i> is a major species. Stands occur in playas where the subsoils contain higher concentrations of sodium (Paris and Paris 1974, Bergman and Marcus 1976). Holpp (1977) described vegetation from 10 playas in Campbell County, Wyoming, that seems very similar to the playas containing this association. His stands generally were dominated by <i>Pascopyrum smithii</i> and contained some wetland species (<i>Juncus arcticus ssp. littoralis, Alopecurus carolinianus</i>), but they showed no consistency in species composition and none contained <i>Eleocharis acicularis</i>. 684248	689943	Northern Oak Barrens are closely related. Both have canopies of 10-30%, but Openings are found on loamier soils and dominated by <i>Quercus macrocarpa</i> and/or <i>Quercus alba</i> (occasionally codominated by <i>Quercus velutina</i>) whereas barrens are found on highly sandy soils and are dominated by <i>Quercus velutina</i> or <i>Quercus ellipsoidalis</i>. Many understory species are shared in common. Understory species that are either unique to or more common in barrens are those that compete well only in acidic, low-nutrient, sandy soils or those that compete well only under very high moisture stress levels (which tend to be higher in barrens than in openings). Species with both high light and high pH or nutrient requirements are found only in Openings.	CEGL002160	<i>Quercus macrocarpa - (Quercus ellipsoidalis) / Schizachyrium scoparium - Koeleria macrantha</i> Wooded Grassland	C	47

685310	688610	in Louisiana at least there may be conceptual overlap with this type. Montz (1978) found both <i>Ruppia</i> and <i>Vallisneria</i> in approximately the same locations and abundance around the eastern edges of Lake Pontchartrain, but noted that "<i>Vallisneria</i> was abundant between depths of 1 foot to 2.5 feet, while <i>Ruppia</i> was abundant closer to the shoreline between depths of 0.5 to 1.5 feet." Wieland (1994a) distinguished between <i>Vallisneria</i> and <i>Ruppia</i> communities based on general salinity tolerances, with <i>Vallisneria</i> preferring oligohaline waters and <i>Ruppia</i> in the mesohaline range. 686587	684561	is similar in that stands of both share shrub layers dominated by <i>Rhus trilobata</i> and herbaceous layers dominated or codominated by <i>Pseudoroegneria spicata</i> and containing a number other graminoids and forbs. Following Mueggler and Stewart (1980), the diagnostic difference between the two associations is the contribution by <i>Festuca idahoensis</i> of at least 5% canopy cover to stands of CEGL001505. Stands containing less than 5% canopy cover of <i>Festuca idahoensis</i> belong to CEGL001120. This treatment differs from that of Hansen and Hoffman (1988), who take the presence of any amount of <i>Festuca idahoensis</i> as indicating vegetation of the <i>Rhus trilobata / Festuca idahoensis</i> habitat type. 687870	689778	Diagnostic features that separate the two types have not been well established, beyond the physiognomic differences between a woodland and a forest. The woodland type frequently occurs as small, scattered stands.	CEGL002079	<i>Betula papyrifera / Corylus cornuta</i> Forest	C	47
689444	687965	a northern oak forest has a more-or-less closed canopy (canopy &gt;80%). It is found on nutrient-poor, drought-prone soils that preclude establishment of more nutrient-demanding trees such as <i>Acer saccharum</i>. Northern oak forests occur on sites protected from intense fires; otherwise they would be converted to oak woodland or <i>Corylus americana</i> shrubland. Even though the canopy is generally closed, the canopy architecture of oaks allows enough sunlight to penetrate to the oak forest understory such that oak forests and oak woodlands share many understory species in common. Oak forests are dominated by shrubs that are taller, since the shrubs are not consumed by intense fires. These taller shrubs produce enough shade to reduce the herbaceous component of oak forests in comparison to oak woodlands. Some understory species common in oak woodlands appear unable to compete with the shade of shrubs and saplings in oak forests.	CEGL002078	<i>Quercus velutina / Carex pensylvanica</i> Forest	C	47
683694	687965	is dominated by <i>Quercus velutina</i>. In Wisconsin, these two species hybridize and traditionally <i>Quercus velutina</i> is treated as occurring south of the tension zone and <i>Quercus ellipsoidalis</i> north of it. However, this type has also been reported in Iowa, Illinois and Indiana.	CEGL002078	<i>Quercus velutina / Carex pensylvanica</i> Forest	C	47

684248	689444	Northern Oak Woodland has a higher canopy cover (30-80%) than Oak Openings, and is found on sites where fire is less frequent. <i>Quercus alba</i> assumes greater importance in this community, <i>Quercus macrocarpa</i> assumes lesser importance (although it is still a canopy codominant), and canopy codominance on more mesic sites is often shared by <i>Quercus rubra</i>. Species shared with Oak Openings but more common in Oak Woodlands tend to be those that are more shade-tolerant or less drought-tolerant. 686468	686202	Hansen and Hoffman (1988) state that <i>Pinus ponderosa / Andropogon</i> spp. community is a seral stage of the <i>Pinus ponderosa / Carex heliophila</i> Habitat Type and predict that as stands become older and canopies close <i>Schizachyrium scoparium</i> is replaced by <i>Carex inops ssp. heliophila</i>. 683348	687266		CEGL000556	<i>Quercus macrocarpa / Corylus americana - Amelanchier alnifolia</i> Woodland	C	47
684331	687266	northern tallgrass prairie, and adjacent plains, bur oak-dominated only.	CEGL000556	<i>Quercus macrocarpa / Corylus americana - Amelanchier alnifolia</i> Woodland	C	47
689444	687266	dry oak woodland is somewhat related. Both communities have canopies of 30-80%, but opening woodlands are found on loamier soils and dominated by <i>Quercus alba, Quercus macrocarpa</i>, and <i>Quercus rubra</i> (reaching dominance on more mesic stands only). Dry oak woodlands are found on droughty, sandy soils and are dominated by <i>Quercus ellipsoidalis, Quercus velutina</i> and <i>Quercus alba</i>. Their highly droughty, low-fertility soils lead to low fuel loads that often allow for only low-intensity fires. Woody individuals which survive the sapling stage generally reach canopy size as the intensities of fire in this community are rarely high enough to kill overstory trees (Anderson 1991). Many understory species are shared in common between dry-mesic oak woodlands and dry oak woodlands. Understory species that are either unique to or more common in dry oak woodlands are those that compete well only in acidic, low-nutrient sandy soils or those that compete well only under more droughty conditions. Conversely, species unique to or more common in dry-mesic oak woodlands tend to be more competitive under lower moisture stress conditions and/or prefer more alkaline conditions.	CEGL000556	<i>Quercus macrocarpa / Corylus americana - Amelanchier alnifolia</i> Woodland	C	47

860215	860217	Where mesomorphic tree growth forms are &gt;10% in canopy, and are irregular in structure in the understory (i.e., natural processes occur for tree saplings, seedlings, herbs and shrubs), stands may better fit here (e.g., tree plantations where the ground layer is not managed or eliminated). 860211	860216	Desert grassland growth forms currently are not distinguished from temperate (mesomorphic) grasslands, and, where these grasslands lack xeromorphic shrubs, there may be no growth forms that provide xeromorphic criteria. In addition, the transition from dry temperate grassland to cool or warm semi-desert may be challenging, and rely more on floristics than growth forms. Desert grasslands lacking many xeromorphic associates in the sense of those in the southwestern United States (New Mexico, Texas, or Arizona) may be considered monsoonal and, thus, could be considered mesomorphic grasslands. Further review is needed.	C03	Desert & Semi-Desert	CT	101
860216	860211	Desert grasslands typically include xeromorphic shrubs and trees, which place them in the Xeromorphic class. Environmental drivers and stressors can cause desert grasslands to cross thresholds into desert scrub. They may also cause dry mesomorphic grasslands with small-leaved shrubs to appear similar to xeromorphic grasslands (e.g., shortgrass prairie in the North American Great Plains).	C02	Shrub & Herb Vegetation	CT	101
860216	860213	In montane deserts, there may be a transition from cool semi-desert to alpine that may be difficult to distinguish.	C04	Polar & High Montane Scrub, Grassland & Barrens	CT	101
860216	860218	This class is restricted to open rock vegetation where nonvascular vegetation is at least 10% and where vascular plants, if present, are mesomorphic.	C06	Open Rock Vegetation	CT	101
860218	860211	In moist climates, cliff, talus, scree, and rock outcrops can contain inclusions of mesomorphic vegetation, but the lithomorphic substrate limits their cover. Where mesomorphic cover is &gt;10% of total vascular vegetation (excluding ferns and allies), the vegetation is placed in this class.	C02	Shrub & Herb Vegetation	CT	101
860218	860213	In either extreme alpine habitats or in polar deserts, the vegetation will be limited to growing on rocks and become so sparse as to qualify as lithomorphic vegetation. But where the vegetation typically has &gt;10% cover of total vascular vegetation (excluding ferns and allies), and is dominated by cryomorphic growth forms, it belongs in this class. This class also includes stands in polar regions where the vascular vegetation has extensive moss or fruticose or foliose lichen (but not crustose lichen) and is on mineral soil (i.e., lichen tundra vegetation).	C04	Polar & High Montane Scrub, Grassland & Barrens	CT	101
860218	860216	Dry habitats with sparse vegetation on rocky surfaces. When xeromorphic plants have &gt;10% cover on rocky substrates, or, if &lt;10%, are the dominant growth present, stands are classified as xeromorphic vegetation.	C03	Desert & Semi-Desert	CT	101
860213	860218	This class is restricted to cryptogam-dominated sites associated with mesomorphic vegetation, as found in tropical, temperate and boreal vegetation regions.	C06	Open Rock Vegetation	CT	101
860213	860216	In high montane deserts, the xeromorphic desert growth forms will transition to cryomorphic growth forms. Review is needed to see where issues may arise between temperate alpine and dry deserts or tropical high montane puna and high deserts.	C03	Desert & Semi-Desert	CT	101
860213	860211	Distinguishing cryomorphic vegetation from mesomorphic vegetation can be a challenge in both arctic and alpine regions. Here we allow mesomorphic extensions into the cryomorphic climatic zone to be retained in the mesomorphic class (e.g., boreal mesomorphic tall willow shrublands along arctic drainages, or the tropics, lower elevation expressions of high montane pramo and puna in South America).	C02	Shrub & Herb Vegetation	CT	101
860211	860218	Sparsely vegetated sand dunes are similar to this class, but the vascular species present are typically mesomorphic, with adaptations to rooting in sand (psammophytic); crustose lichens and ferns are typically absent. Unstable scree may also contain scattered mesomorphic herbs and little to no nonvascular vegetation, but for now are retained in this class.	C06	Open Rock Vegetation	CT	101
860211	860213	Distinguishing cryomorphic vegetation from mesomorphic can be a challenge in both arctic and alpine regions. Here we allow mesomorphic extensions into the cryomorphic climatic zone to be retained in the mesomorphic class (e.g., boreal mesomorphic tall willow shrublands along arctic drainageways are excluded from Cryomorphic Vegetation), whereas prostrate or dwarf willow species are treated as part of the cryomorphic class. 860217	860216	Occasionally xeromorphic trees may be sufficiently dense to form woodland stands (e.g., saguaro, Joshua tree, microphyllous-leaved mesquite woodlands, tropical thorn woodlands). 860217	860211	When grasses and shrubs dominate the ground layer and tree cover is near but &gt;10%, is clumped, or overtopped by grasses and shrubs, there may be cases where assignment to this class is preferable. However, in tropical upland savanna regions, stands may have 40% tree cover, where trees are &lt;8 m tall, tree regeneration is sparse to absent, and there is a substantial graminoid layer. 860241	860236	Greatly simplified set of growth forms, primarily more conical-shaped spruce, fir and larch, and simple-leaved boreal hardwoods of <i>Betula</i> spp. and <i>Populus</i> spp. Moss layer often very prominent. 860407	860357	The freshwater aquatic D049 intergrades with D065 along a salinity gradient in coastal estuaries, with D049 occupying salinity regimes of freshwater to mildly oligohaline (usually, less than 1 practical salinity unit (psu)) and D065 in oligohaline to middle mesohaline regimes. Taxa such as <i>Stuckenia pectinata, Zannichellia palustris</i>, and <i>Potamogeton perfoliatus</i> are common to both divisions, but the presence of <i>Ruppia</i> spp. usually will be diagnostic of D065, while predominance of more strictly freshwater taxa (e.g., <i>Vallisneria, Myriophyllum, Ceratophyllum, Elodea, Najas, Potamogeton</i> other than <i>Potamogeton perfoliatus, Hydrilla, Heteranthera</i>), over salt-tolerant taxa (e.g., <i>Ruppia</i> spp., <i>Stuckenia pectinata, Zannichellia palustris, Potamogeton perfoliatus</i>) generally will indicate D049.	D049	North American Freshwater Aquatic Vegetation	C	104
860407	860303	may intergrade with D065 along a similar salinity gradient in warm-temperate to subtropical regions, and the cosmopolitan <i>Ruppia maritima</i> (including monospecific stands) is an element of both divisions. Within the U.S., the seagrasses of D063 occur along the Atlantic and Gulf coasts of the southeastern United States from South Carolina to Texas and also in the Caribbean, Hawaii, and other tropical Pacific islands. The predominance of the associates <i>Halophila</i> spp., <i>Halodule</i> spp., <i>Cymodocea filiformis</i>, and/or <i>Thalassia testudinum</i> and the absence of the associates <i>Stuckenia pectinata, Zannichellia palustris, Potamogeton perfoliatus</i>, and/or freshwater species will indicate D063. Vascular plant stands that are monospecific with <i>Ruppia maritima</i> may have to be assigned by water salinity and/or by associated biota other than vascular plants.	D063	Tropical Saltwater Vegetation	CT	104
860407	860293	intergrades with D065 along a salinity gradient in coastal estuaries along the North American Pacific coast from Baja California to Alaska and along the North American Atlantic coast from North Carolina to subarctic Canada. The seagrasses in D064 occupy salinity regimes of upper mesohaline or higher (approximately, greater than 10-15 practical salinity units (psu)), whereas D065 occupies oligohaline to middle mesohaline regimes (except in inland and/or hydrologically isolated settings, which may be hypersaline). Except for <i>Ruppia maritima</i>, there is generally little floristic overlap between the divisions. The presence of <i>Zostera</i> spp. usually will be diagnostic of the former, while that of <i>Zannichellia palustris, Stuckenia pectinata, Potamogeton</i> spp., and other species that can grow in freshwater will indicate the latter. Because of the wide salinity tolerance of <i>Ruppia maritima</i>, stands strongly dominated by that species may be problematic to assign. In these cases, the predominance of these other species as minor associates will often make the determination. Vascular plant stands that are monospecific with <i>Ruppia maritima</i> occur in both divisions and may have to be assigned by water salinity and/or by associated biota other than vascular plants.	D064	Temperate Seagrass Aquatic Vegetation	C	104
860348	872761	abuts stands of D007, where the former occupy the middle to higher elevations of montane areas (e.g., the Klamath Mountains, Cascade, Sierra Nevada, Coast, Transverse, and Peninsular ranges). The two divisions also intergrade along a latitudinal gradient at or slightly above sea level elevations along the northern California coast. Species such as <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii, Quercus kelloggii, Quercus garryana</i>, and <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> may be important components of vegetation units within both divisions. Floristically, evergreen broad-leaved (hardwood) tree species and closed-cone conifers are more characteristic of D007, whereas the conifer genera <i>Tsuga, Sequoia, Sequoiadendron, Calocedrus, Chamaecyparis, Thuja, Abies</i>, and <i>Picea</i> and species such as <i>Pinus lambertiana, Pinus jeffreyi</i>, and <i>Acer macrophyllum</i> are more characteristic of D192. D320	Circumpolar Arctic & Subarctic Freshwater Marsh & Wet Meadow	C	104
933578	933574	The range of D323 abuts that D322 in the Atlantic and Gulf coastal plains from the Maritime Provinces to Texas. Generally, species that are restricted to the coastal plains (e.g., <i>Amaranthus cannabinus, Carex hyalinolepis, Cladium mariscus ssp. jamaicense, Eleocharis equisetoides, Ilex glabra, Leersia hexandra, Morella cerifera, Nelumbo lutea, Panicum hemitomon, Panicum tenerum, Proserpinaca pectinata, Spartina cynosuroides, Vaccinium formosum, Vaccinium fuscatum, Zizaniopsis miliacea</i>) will indicate stands of D322. Genera such as <i>Andropogon, Eriocaulon, Fimbristylis, Fuirena, Paspalum, Rhynchospora, Sarracenia</i>, and <i>Xyris</i> have greater prominence and a higher diversity of species in D322, in the southern part of the ranges of the two divisions. The floristic distinctions between the divisions in the northern part of their ranges, where there are fewer characteristically warm-temperate taxa, is not as clear. 860293	860303	intergrades with D064 along a climate gradient in the southeastern Atlantic coast, with the boundary near the southern limit of the range of <i>Zostera marina</i> (approximately the North Carolina - South Carolina border). As with the conceptual boundary with D065, <i>Ruppia maritima</i> is characteristic of both divisions. In mixed stands near this boundary, the presence of <i>Zostera marina</i> indicates D063, while monospecific stands of <i>Halodule wrightii</i> or stands with both <i>Halodule wrightii</i> and <i>Ruppia maritima</i>, but without <i>Zostera marina</i>, generally will be assigned D064. Other taxa that are characteristic of D063 in the southeastern United States (<i>Halophila</i> spp., <i>Cymodocea filiformis</i>, and <i>Thalassia testudinum</i>) have ranges that do not overlap that of <i>Zostera marina</i>. On the Pacific coast of North America, the boundary between the two divisions occurs well south of the U.S. (south of Baja California).	D063	Tropical Saltwater Vegetation	CT	104
860293	860407	intergrades with D064 along a salinity gradient, with D065 occupying salinity regimes of upper mesohaline or higher (approximately greater than 10 practical salinity units (psu)) and D064 in oligohaline to lower mesohaline regimes. Except for <i>Ruppia maritima</i>, there is generally little floristic overlap between the divisions. The presence of <i>Zostera</i> spp. and/or <i>Phyllospadix</i> spp. usually will be diagnostic of D064, while that of <i>Zannichellia palustris, Stuckenia pectinata, Potamogeton</i> spp., and other species that can grow in freshwater will indicate D065. Because of the wide salinity tolerance of <i>Ruppia maritima</i>, stands strongly dominated by that species may be problematic to assign. In these cases, the predominance of these other species as minor associates will often make the determination. Vascular plant stands that are monospecific with <i>Ruppia maritima</i> occur in both divisions and may have to be assigned by water salinity and/or by associated biota other than vascular plants.	D065	Temperate Estuarine & Inland Brackish Aquatic Vegetation	C	104
860374	860325	Sparsely vegetated upper beach stands of D026 intergrade with sparser (incipient) stands of D034 in the middle to inland side of barrier islands and spits, and the two units share some salt-tolerant ruderal species. Stands that can be assigned to the salt marsh D034 can be distinguished by a greater prevalence of hydrophytic, rather than upland, species, including pioneer individuals of the eventually dominant graminoid species (e.g., <i>Spartina alterniflora, Distichlis spicata</i>). 860211	860215	Agricultural grasslands in this class may be regularly mowed, hayed or grazed, and have an atypical "cut" structure periodically throughout the season, and may be dominated by exotic grasses. Developed grasslands in this class have a very regularly, often very low, cropped structure because of regular cutting or mowing (even weekly during the growing season).	CCL01	Agricultural & Developed Vegetation	CT	111
860217	860215	Forests found in urban parks and lawns may have an irregular horizontal spacing but a highly regular or mowed understory and are placed in this developed vegetation class. Forests, such as orchards and forest plantations, typically have either a very regularly spaced tree canopy (often pruned or trained) and/or plowed or regularly manipulated ground layer (e.g., tree-shaded shrub or herb crops).	CCL01	Agricultural & Developed Vegetation	CT	111
860214	860215	These cultural wetlands may have a vegetation structure that is regularly managed (e.g., rice paddies), the water levels may be regularly manipulated, or the shores of the wetland may be highly modified by concrete, berms, etc.	CCL01	Agricultural & Developed Vegetation	CT	111
